title: Land inside protected areas or OECMs
description: Evolution of land considered a Protected Area (PA) or Other Effective Conservation Measures (OECM), from 2000 to 2050 differentiating per land cover type

legend.label: Figure description
legend.description: The figure show the total land under protected areas or Other Effectice Conservation Measures (OECM) as reported by WDPA. We do not disagregate OECM per land cover type. According to the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework, we should aim at 30% of terristerial land under PA or OECM by 2030.
Land under OECM whatever the land cover type

notes: Historical values come from WDPA. Values from 2000 to 2010 are constant to the 2010 level.

title: Land where natural processes predominate
description: Evolution of land where natural processes predominate (LNPP), i.e. area where there is low human interruption and where biodiveristy can flourish, from 2000 to 2050,differentiating per land cover type

legend.label: Figure description
legend.description: The figure shows the total land where natural processes predominate (LNPP) outside productive land. LNPP is a metric created by FABLE to represent areas where biodivesity can naturally flourish. It includes low impact area (Jacobson et al, 2019), key biodiversity areas (BirdLife International 2019) and intact forest landscapes (Potapov et al, 2017). Mature forest and natural areas refer to forest and natural areas that were already present in 2000 while new forest and natural areas refers to afforested or reforested areas and abandonned agricultural land from 2000 onwards. According to the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework, we should aim at no loss in mature LNPP and a 15% increase in total LNPP by 2050.
LNPP in mature other natural land
LNPP in new other natural land

notes: Historical values are computed by the FABLE Secretariat. Values from 2000 to 2010 are constant to the 2010 level.

legend.label: Figure description
legend.description: Mature forest refers to forest areas that were already present in 2000. The global objective is to have zero deforestation in mature forest areas from 2030 onwards. In the FABLE Calculator, forest loss is driven by cropland, pasture and/or urban expansion.

title: Cropland area under agroecological practices
description: Evolution of total cropland area, both under conventional and agroecological practices

legend.label: Figure description
legend.description: Agroecological practices is an umbrella term for any practice that is distinct from intensively managed monocultures such as cover crops, cultivar mixtures, embedded natural land, reduced tillage, organic farming or a mix of them. In our model, agroecological practice coverage is expressed as a percentage of total cropland. According to the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework, we should aim at 50% of cropland area managed under biodierversity-friendly practices 2030.
Cropland area managed under agroecological practices
Cropland area managed under non-agroecological practices

notes: Baseline data on agroecological practices coverage is made by FABLE, please refer to the Agroecology module documentation (2024) for more information.
